    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26.77-79_0001"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">77</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        Lake Ozarks, Mo.
                        March 30th. '58
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Dr. John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Columbia, Missouri</addrLine>
                    </address>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Dr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I hope that you will excuse my long delay in answering your most welcome letter of sometime ago. It was with pride that we read your letter of approval and planned the staging of "Jamie".</p>
                
                <p>Since that time I have been forced to take several weeks absence due to a death of my mother and upon my return, found it impossible to continue our plans as concerned the three one-act plays for the home contest. This was disheartening to both the students and myself, but we agreed that we could never do it justice in the few days which remained. Therefore, we selected a more easily staged one-act and were gratified to receive an Excellent and Best Serious play, plus honorable mention of one character, recently at Warrensburg.</p>
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26.77-79_0002"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">78</fw>
                
                <p>I know that had we been able to complete plans, "Jamie" would have been a work of which I would have been very proud. I suggested completion of plans, disregarding the element of contest work, but the desire for a Senior class play now renders that impossible.</p>
                
                <p>I am very grateful to both you and Mrs. Neihardt for your encouragement and consideration. We had looked forward to having you folks as honorary guests on our opening night.</p>
                
                <p>Please do not think my negligence in writing was due to lack of appreciation, but rather due to circumstances beyond my control.</p>
                
                <p>I would feel honored to have you keep the script. I would also consider it a priviledge meeting you and hope to realize that pleasure in the future.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Thanking you both again, I remain</salute>
                    <salute>Yours Most Sincerely</salute>
                    
                    <signed>Max D. Carpenter</signed>
                    <signed>Max D. Carpenter
                    School of the Osage</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
            
            
